english:
  title: 'Eulogy for the Portrait of Lord Jeong, Attendant of the Inner Court: With Preface'
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: "Lord Lee, Minister of the Outer Gate and Prince of Gwangpyeong, together with several generals, recovered the capital in the year of Imyin. The commander of all troops was Lord Jeong Seyun, Vice Minister and General of the Eungyanggun. Three marshals, jealous that the commander's merit stood higher than their own, ordered their subordinates to strike him down and destroy him. Though these three marshals met justice and perished, the world's sorrow for Lord Jeong remains unresolved even now. Lord Gwangpyeong reflected: \"Lord Jeong's name shall endure eternal and imperishable. Yet his likeness would be unknown to posterity—is this not cause for lamentation?\" He also said: \"The painting of heroes in the Hall of the Immortals was the custom of old, yet it is practiced no longer. Better to commission his portrait and make seasonal offerings before it.\" When completed, Lord Gwangpyeong requested that I, Lee Saek of Hansan, compose this eulogy. Since I too served the late King as an Attendant Commissioner alongside Lord Gwangpyeong, I came to know that Lord Jeong was no ordinary man. He served his ruler with unwavering loyalty, never stooping to curry favor. He held his resolve firm, never wavering in the slightest. When, in the year of Sinchuk, the court fled southward to Buzhou, both sovereign and subject looked anxiously northward—what need to speak of such anguish? Yet Lord Jeong boldly offered himself for this mission. Within mere months, the realm was restored to peace. Could this be mere chance? \n\nIn the days of King Hyeonjong, Minister Kang Hantsan petitioned for a southern journey in the year of Gyeongsu, and repelled invaders from the north in the year of Muo—his achievements were indeed remarkable. In recent times, when the Kims of Geumsan invaded our borders, Zhao Chong and Kim Jwilli accomplished much. When the rebel Mao attacked Seogyeong in the year of Gihae, General Lee Seunggyeong's strength was great. Yet these were all merely regional matters, not comparable to Minister Kang's two great strategies born from a single person. King Hyeonjong reached the capital at Geumsung; King Gongmin reached Buzhou—alas, how can this be endured in speech? Lord Jeong participated in the decision to journey south, and moreover was able to command all armies and drive back the enemy forces, achieving great merit standing alone. His accomplishment rivals even Minister Kang's. Yet when Minister Kang returned victorious, King Hyeonjong himself went forth to the suburbs to receive him and composed verses to praise him. Thus Lord Jeong's misfortune was King Gongmin's sorrow. Heaven, why was this so? Alas, how sorrowful! How sorrowful!\n\nThose who in ages to come pay respect before Lord Jeong's portrait, knowing it was created by Lord Gwangpyeong, will surely arise in reverence even a thousand years hence and say: \"Lord Jeong indeed possessed great merit. Yet without Lord Gwangpyeong, how would we ever behold Lord Jeong's countenance?\" Thus Lord Gwangpyeong's love of virtue shall shine forth ever brighter. Can one not speak of this at length? The Jeong clan hailed from Changtaek County in Gwangju. Lord Jeong was a meritorious minister of the eleventh year of King Gongmin's reign. His younger brother was named Seyun; he left no son.\n\nThe Eulogy reads:\n\nAh, Lord Jeong! Simple without, steadfast within,\nA meritorious minister of Gongmin, summoned in Byeongsin's year.\nWhen bandits swept through the Middle Kingdom and invaded our realm,\nWe retreated before their onslaught, yet you marched forth to meet them.\nYou defeated them utterly, yet your own men brought you down—\nBoth the slayers and the slain have vanished into dust.\nAlas, such thoughtlessness! Minister Kang's deeds fade into antiquity,\nYet your greatness stands equal to his.\nWithout our Lord Gwangpyeong, who would have painted, who would have recorded?\nSongak Mountain stands green and proud; our hall shines majestic.\nYour spirit, Lord Jeong, shall echo through ages without end."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Year of Imyin (壬寅) refers to 1362, when Korean forces under General Yi Ingyom recaptured Seoul from the Red Turbans.
  - key: ''
    value: King Gongmin was forced to flee to Buzhou (in Anhui, China) during the invasion of 1361, resulting in considerable hardship for the Korean court.
  - key: ''
    value: Minister Kang Hantsan of the Hyeonjong era (r. 1009-1031) represents an idealized historical parallel—a loyal minister who served through multiple crises.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to painting in the Hall of the Immortals (Lingyan Ge) alludes to the Tang Dynasty custom of honoring meritorious officials through portraiture, suggesting a comparison between Chinese imperial traditions and Korean court practices.
